The '''scope of review''' refers generally to the [[rights|right]] to have an issue raised on [[appeal]]. Which essentially entails whether an issue was preserved by or available to an [[appellant]] on appeal.

For example, in the [[United States]], a party can preserve an issue for appeal by raising an [[Objection (law)|objection]] at [[trial (law)|trial]].
